Coho salmon fishing.

Every fall tens of thousands of Coho salmon migrate the Fraser river. I target them in three key tributaries where we have the opportunity to harvest hatchery(clipped adipose fin) fish.

I have many methods to target coho and have dialled in when to apply these methods to match the river conditions. Coho aggressively chase spoons, spinners and flys. In some situations we will float fish salmon eggs or beads.

Timing is important! We fish coho September 25 up until November 25. Of course river conditions dictate the success and abundance of fish, none the less you will leave with a new skill set to chase coho on your own after a day spent with me. 

I always offer coho as an extra on our Sturgeon trips in the appropriate run timing (September 25-November 25) Just make sure to ask while booking!

Chinook fishing.

I target Chinook salmon every fall in the Chilliwack/Vedder river with my clients. We offer this fishery September 15 / October 15. 
 
 The combination of conditions, fish pushing, and tides are key components for success.

Chinook are aggressive biters. Spinners, spoons, a large twitched Jig, roe, and soft beads all work great.

If you would like to add chinook fishing to your sturgeon trip, let me know while booking.

Chum Salmon fishing.

Abundant, hard fighting, aggressive biters, are a few words to explain chum. 

I typically fish chums with my clients October to the end of November. We fish them in the Harrison river, our main method is float fishing a jig. This is a great fishery for new anglers because the chum’s abundance typically makes them fairly easy to catch. 

Some people think chum salmon are no good for eating, this is false. They are great on the bbq, smoked, or deep fried. (I personally like to smoke all my fish. When harvest opportunities are available I get my share!) 

If fishing chum interests you, we offer it as an additional option while sturgeon fishing with us. Again, run timing is October to the end of November. 

(When fishing regulations allow)

Pink salmon fishing.

Fraser valley pink salmon runs occur only on odd years (2021/2023) they typically start showing up mid August and run through October. 

Pinks are so fun to fish for, their abundance and willingness to bite makes for a great day. Our favourite technique to catch pinks is twitching a jig, or retrieving a spinner or a spoon. (Another important thing to know is all your lures/Jigs need to be PINK.)

I start fishing Pinks with clients at the beginning of September right up until October 1. If you would like to add pink salmon to your fishing trip let me know at the time of booking.

Summer Chinooks!

Personally one of my favourite fishery’s. Every summer a few of our local flows get a small run of hatchery produced Red chinook.

To be successful in this fishery it takes a-lot of ground work, time, effort and of course right place, right time. These fish are extremely hard fighting and not afraid to sit in strong deep currents. 

Roe, soft beads, and spinners are all great options to catch summer chinook. It is a fairly short run, peaking mid, to late July. I do not guide summer Chinooks,  just thought I would share a local fishery I love to partake in. 

Happiest of holidays everyone! 
Brandon.

I hope everyone had an excellent few days spent with family, friends and ate some amazing food! 

 Over the winter months when I am not on the Fraser, you will most likely find me on a local flow chasing winter steelhead. A passion I share with many, many local anglers. 

The time and effort required to be consistently successful in this fishery is ridiculous, but so rewarding. Covering many miles of river, spending countless hours may result in a few hook ups, or none. 

The key is relentless effort! I do not guide steelhead, just wanted to share a fishery I am passionate about and wish everyone the best in 2023. I am sure I will be seeing some of you on the river soon!

Brandon

Good day everyone!

I have been getting alot of questions about our fishing trips. Here is a brief overview of our equipment, season, trip options and capacity. 

Boats. 
We have two custom covered Jet boats. One being 22 ft and the other being 20ft. Both have heaters, side image sounders and are equipped with side cradle slings for proper Sturgeon handling and data collection. All of our equipment, right down to our fishing reels are regularly maintained. We have no room for error. 

Season.
We are open year round. Over the winter months we operate when we have breaks in the winter weather conditions. Once March rolls around we are full swing until the end of November. Each month provides the opportunity for trophy Sturgeon. The only time I suggest a time frame is when anglers fishing with us would like to have a chance at catching salmon as well. (September 15 through November 15) 

Trips.
We offer a few trip options. Our most popular trip is an 8 hour fishing day, this trips starts out of Chilliwack and we will head up towards Hope or down towards mission depending on where we have found feeding sturgeon. We also have a 10 hour trip option. As we all know more time on the water ups your chance of encountering that true fish of a lifetime. This year we are also offering wilderness trout fishing adventures on some unnamed River systems.(contact for details) we also are offering Fraser canyon trips. (Above Hope BC) 

Capacity.
Our boats can fish up to five guests. (Six if you include the guide) We have aligned with other companies to ensure we can accommodate any group size, and have access to many more boats outside our company boats. Another important note is that all our trips are private. This means if you book a boat for two people, that boat is yours. No shared trips here. 

Booking.
All our booking is done online through our website. Click book now, choose your date(s) deposit is collected and in the checkout you have the option to add on a BBQ lunch. After this, a detailed itinerary is sent along with your booking confirmation and receipt.

Thanks for taking the time to read this. Don’t ever hesitate to Dm me here for a fishing report!

Brandon

Sturgeon fishing bc 

British Columbia is home to some of the best sturgeon fishing in the world. The Fraser River is home to the largest population of white sturgeon in the world, making it an ideal spot for anglers looking to experience the thrill of catching one of these majestic fish. Whether you’re a novice or a seasoned pro, the Fraser River offers a unique experience for all levels of anglers.

Sturgeon fishing in British Columbia is a popular pastime for locals and visitors alike. Many anglers come to the Fraser River to try their luck at catching a trophy-sized sturgeon. The Fraser River is home to a variety of sturgeon species, including white, green, and shovelnose sturgeon. Anglers can choose from a variety of techniques to catch sturgeon, the best technique is a fixed bait presented on the river bottom.

When fishing for sturgeon in British Columbia, it’s important to follow the regulations that are in place to protect these fish. All anglers must have a valid fishing license and Sturgeon tag.

When fishing for sturgeon in British Columbia, it’s important to use the right gear. Heavy-duty rods and reels are recommended, along with heavy-duty line and lures. Anglers should also use a fish finder to locate the best spots to cast their lines.

Sturgeon fishing in British Columbia can be an exciting and rewarding experience. With the right preparation and knowledge, anglers can have a successful and enjoyable time out on the Fraser River.
